        ASEAN gets company
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/asean-gcc-china-summit-malaysia.jpg" alt="Leaders from ASEAN, China, and the Gulf Cooperation Council at the first trilateral summit in Kuala Lumpur, highlighting regional cooperation in response to global trade tensions." href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>
          Malaysia is the current chair of ASEAN, which also includes Brunei, Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam. Credits: Bernama</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) held its first <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-may-25-spotlight-h1-1-three-way-summit" target="_blank">three-way summit</a> with China and the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia. The meeting emphasized the importance of closer cooperation in addressing global trade uncertainty. This is especially important given the high US tariffs, which have significantly impacted the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-may-25-spotlight-h1-2-economies-of-southeast-asia" target="_blank">economies of Southeast Asia</a>.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
      Malaysian PM Ibrahim stressed the importance of unity in the changing geopolitical landscape and the decline of multilateralism. He also said that trade agreements with the US must not hurt other ASEAN members. China’s Premier Li Qiang supports a stronger trilateral relationship, presenting China as a dependable partner during global decoupling.</p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The high-level attendees included Qatar’s Emir, Kuwait’s Crown Prince, and the Prime Ministers of Vietnam and Thailand. Analysts say the summit is a clever move by ASEAN to diversify its partnerships and strengthen its role in global trade amid uncertainty. </p>
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        ASEAN has upheld a policy of neutrality, engaging with Beijing and Washington. However, six of the bloc’s members were among the worst hit by Trump’s tariffs, between 32% and 49%, which came as a blow. </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
