          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">
          Alberta separation</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: Alberta is unlikely to separate, but the growing sentiment is sending a message to Carney.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Alberta is moving <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-may-25-spotlight-h1-3-closer-to-a-referendum" target="_blank">closer to a referendum</a> on leaving Canada. This push stems from concerns about federal control over natural resources and climate regulations. Their dissent follows Trump’s taunts to annex Canada and the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-may-25-spotlight-h1-4-re-election-of-a-liberal-federal-government" target="_blank">re-election of a Liberal federal government</a>. Alberta’s Premier Danielle Smith says she does not support independence, but she has simplified it for groups to invoke a vote. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The need for a referendum reveals deep frustration among Albertans as they seek more control, especially over the oil and gas industry. Some separatists also believe that joining with the US better aligns with their values. Indigenous leaders have condemned the separatist movement, warning it violates treaty rights and stokes national disunity.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         While complete secession is unlikely due to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-may-25-spotlight-h1-5-constitutional-barriers" target="_blank">constitutional barriers</a>, the push for a referendum shows a province that feels increasingly isolated. Carney, who is from Alberta himself, has a balancing act to perform. </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         He needs to address Alberta’s concerns while avoiding support for the separatist movement. He also needs to consider the priorities of First Nations communities and Quebec, which also have differing concerns from the rest of Canada.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

