      <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
        Sudan’s golden connection
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>
         Summary: Sudan’s gold production has drawn interest from outsiders, such as the UAE and Egypt, into its civil war.</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The Sudanese Armed Forces (SAF) and the paramilitary Rapid Support Forces (RSF) are engaged in a conflict over gold assets, further fueling the war. Artisanal and <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-28-may-25-analysis-h1-6-small-scale-gold-mining" target="_blank">small-scale gold mining</a> represents the majority of Sudan’s gold production. Smugglers move much of this gold to the UAE via Chad, Egypt, Eritrea, and South Sudan. These smuggling routes tie Sudan to a larger regional conflict. Both state and non-state actors play a role.  
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        The war economy thrives on illegal trade and shifts power through gold and fuel exchanges. Major outside players such as the UAE and Egypt gain immensely but risk compromising long-term stability. Lasting peace needs a united international effort and regional cooperation. This should focus on regulating resource flows, disrupting war economies, and tackling the deeper political causes of conflict.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        Sudan’s gold trade fuels internal strife and worsens regional issues. The SAF exports gold to Egypt to bypass the UAE and fund its war. The high gains encourage smuggling, while a significant amount of this gold still reaches the UAE, thereby undermining control. With formal state revenues collapsing, control over gold mines has become a strategic priority for both factions. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
        External players from around the region influence Sudan’s war through political, military, and monetary ties to the gold industry. Despite US diplomatic efforts and sanctions, the US’s focus on Middle East issues limits its impact on Sudan’s war and its regional backers. Without international measures to disrupt the gold-for-guns trade, the conflict risks Sudan’s natural wealth continuing to fund its collapse. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
